Part 2: Data and Analysis

In the midterm 1 folder there is a second folder called data. Inside the data folder, there is a .csv file called anolis_dat.csv. These data came from D. Luke Mahler, Liam J. Revell, Richard E. Glor, Jonathan B. Losos, ECOLOGICAL OPPORTUNITY AND THE RATE OF MORPHOLOGICAL EVOLUTION IN THE DIVERSIFICATION OF GREATER ANTILLEAN ANOLES, Evolution, Volume 64, Issue 9, 1 September 2010, Pages 27312745. The original research article is included in the data folder.

Anolis is a genus of lizards commonly known as anoles. Anoles are found throughout the Americas, but are especially diverse in the Caribbean. The data include morphological measurements for Anolis lizards from the islands of the Greater Antilles. These data can be used to study patterns of morphological evolution and adaptation in Anolis lizards.

The variables include:
- species: Species name of the anole lizard.
- habitat: Habitat type where the lizard was found.
- hindlimb_length_mm: Length of the lizards hindlimbs (in millimeters).
- tail_length_mm: Length of the lizards tail (in millimeters).
- body_length_mm: Length of the lizards body (in millimeters).
- toepad_lamellae_count: Count of lamellae on the lizards toepads.
- island: Island where the lizard was found.

Question 7. (4 points) Is sampling equal across islands? Create a plot to visualize the number of anole species sampled from each island. Be sure to label your axes and add a title.

anolis %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=island))+
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(fill=island))+
  labs(title="Number of Species Across Islands", x="Island", y="Species Count")

The sampling of anole species isnt equal across islands as Cuba and Hispaniola have the majority of species while Jamacia and Puerto Rico have the lowest number of species.

Question 10. (4 points) The morphology of anoles varies based on their habitat. How does the range of hindlimb length compare among different habitats? Create a plot to visualize the distribution of hindlimb lengths across habitat types. Be sure to label your axes and add a title.

anolis %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=habitat, y=hindlimb_length_mm))+
  geom_boxplot(mapping=aes(fill=habitat))+
  labs(title="Distribution of Hindlimb Lengths Across Different Habitats", x="Habitat Type", y="Hindlimb Length (mm)")

Trunk-ground species have the highest range of hindlimb lengths, grass-bush and trunk-crown species have lower, but similar ranges to each other compared to trunk-ground species, and twig species have the lowest range of hindlimb lengths out of all the habitats.

Question 11. (4 points) The plot above is compelling, but dont we expect larger lizards to have longer limbs? What about tail length? Shouldnt longer lizards have longer tails? To correct for this, make two new columns: 1. ratio_of_hindlimb_to_body, and 2. ratio_of_tail_to_body. Dont forget to add these columns to the anolis data frame.

anolis <- anolis %>% 
  mutate(ratio_of_hindlimb_to_body=hindlimb_length_mm/body_length_mm,
         ratio_of_tail_to_body=tail_length_mm/body_length_mm)
anolis %>% 
  relocate(ratio_of_hindlimb_to_body, ratio_of_tail_to_body) %>% 
  slice_head(n=5)

Question 12. (4 points) Create a new plot that examines the distribution of ratio_of_hindlimb_to_body across habitat types. How does this plot differ from the one you made in Problem 10? Be sure to label your axes and add a title.

anolis %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=habitat, y=ratio_of_hindlimb_to_body))+
  geom_boxplot(mapping=aes(fill=habitat))+
  labs(title="Ratio of Hindlimb to Body Across Habitat Types", x="Habitat Type", y="Ratio of Hindlimb to Body Length")

A noticeable difference I see between these two plots is that grass-bush has the 2nd highest distribution of ratio of hindlimb length to body length in this plot compared to the 2nd lowest distribution of hindlimb length in Question 10s plot. The range of hindlimb lengths of trunk-ground species in Question 10s plot was also noticeably larger than the range of ratio of hindlimb length to body length in this questions plot.

Problem 13. (4 points) A longer tail provides better balance and agility. Create a plot that examines the relationship between body length and tail length. Color the points by habitat type and add a line of best fit. What does this plot suggest about the relationship between body length and tail length? What do you notice about lizards in the Grass-bush habitat? Be sure to label your axes and add a title.

anolis %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=body_length_mm, y=tail_length_mm))+
  geom_point(mapping=aes(color=habitat))+
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se=T)+
  labs(title="Body Length vs. Tail Length", x="Body Length (mm)", y="Tail Length (mm)")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

This plot suggests there is a positive association between body length and tail length. I noticed that most lizards in the grass-bush habitat dont directly follow this association as they have a shorter body length compared to other lizards in different habitats, but also have a long tail length.

Problem 14. (4 points) Toepad lamellae are transverse, plate-like structures found on the ventral surface of the digits. They are a key adaptation that allows anoles to cling to and move efficiently on smooth and vertical surfaces. What is the mean number of toepad lamellae for each habitat type?

anolis %>% 
  distinct(habitat)
## # A tibble: 4  1
##   habitat     
##   <fct>       
## 1 Trunk-ground
## 2 Twig        
## 3 Grass-bush  
## 4 Trunk-crown
anolis %>% 
  filter(habitat=="Trunk-ground") %>% 
  summarize(mean_toepad_trunkground=mean(toepad_lamellae_count))
## # A tibble: 1  1

Problem 15. (5 points) The number of toepad lamellae is significantly different for trunk-crown species. But, is this consistent across all islands? Make a plot that shows the range in number of toepad lamellae by island for trunk-crown species only. Be sure to label your axes and add a title.

anolis %>% 
  filter(habitat=="Trunk-crown") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=island, y=toepad_lamellae_count))+
  geom_boxplot(mapping=aes(fill=island))+
  labs(title="Toepad Lamellae Count of Trunk-Crown Species Across Different Islands", x="Island", y="Toepad Lamellae Count")

The distribution of toepad lamellae for trunk-crown species is uneven across the islands. The median toepad lamellae count significantly different across the islands. Among the different islands, species living in Hispaniola have toepad lamellae counts closest to the mean toepad lamellae count of trunk-crown species.
